# *Limits*

- Limits quantify what happens to the values of a function as we approach a given point.
- This can be defined as: â€œ***the limit asÂ xÂ goes to 6 of f(x) approaches some value L***â€.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/61bd7333-501e-4ebc-96d3-7b8b716daa64/Untitled.png)

- We can read this as: â€œ***the limit asÂ xÂ goes to 6 of f(x) approaches some value L***â€
    - To evaluate this limit, we take points increasingly closer and closer toÂ *6*â€” as close to 6 as we can get, but not 6 itself! We then evaluate where the function is headed at those points.
- If we look at the limit of a function as x approaches a value from one direction, this is called ***aÂ one-sided limit***.
- For example, we might look at the values ofÂ *f(5)*,Â *f(5.9)*,Â *f(5.999)*Â and see if they are trending towards the value ofÂ *f(6)*. This is represented as:

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/3450f501-4d46-4455-b72e-b598877e8bdd/Untitled.png)

- We read this as â€œ***the limit as x approaches 6 from the left side approaches some value L***â€.
- Whereas if we looked at the values ofÂ *f(6.1)*,Â *f(6.01)*,Â *f(6.0005)*Â and see if they are trending towardsÂ *f(6)*, we would represent this as:
    
    ![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/ff8b6a5a-9d71-4c3f-b3cd-f15dc4435c60/Untitled.png)
    
- We read this as â€œ***the limit asÂ xÂ goes to 6 from the right side approaches some value L***â€.

> The limit asÂ *x*Â approaches 6 exists only if the limit asÂ *x*Â approaches 6 from the left side is equal to the limit asÂ *x*Â approaches 6 from the right side.
> 

