# *Limit Definition of a Derivative*

- Suppose we wanted to measure a runnerâ€™s instantaneous speed using a stopwatch. By instantaneous speed, we mean their speed at an exact moment in time.
- Letâ€™s defineÂ *f(t)*Â as the runnerâ€™s distance from the start time at timeÂ *t*. How could we find the runnerâ€™s instantaneous speed at 1 second after the race? We could record their positions at 1 second and sometime second measurement. Then the second time isÂ *x+h*, and the positions at the two times areÂ *f(x)*Â andÂ *f(x+h)*.

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/c341a9a9-e8de-4533-85e4-b0aca7e5c776/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/2886226a-6b67-45fa-9949-e1dffe3d285e/Untitled.png)

> This is called theÂ *derivative at a point*, which is the functionâ€™s slope (rate of change) at a specific point.
> 

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/3672fca1-a5f9-4646-9c7c-3f7579f82de7/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/0c7c7acd-4363-4edc-8e92-064b5a156811/Untitled.png)

