# *The Derivative Function*

- Derivative functions are often denotedÂ ***fâ€™(x)*Â (readÂ *f*Â prime ofÂ *x*)** orÂ ***df/dx*Â (read derivative ofÂ *f*Â atÂ *x*)**.
- If ***f(x)*** represents ***the function value at a pointÂ x***, the corresponding ***derivative functionÂ fâ€™(x)***Â represents ***how a function is changing at the same pointÂ x***.

---

# *Properties of the Derivative Function*

- Letâ€™s say:
    - If *f(t)*Â describes a runnerâ€™s position as a function of time; Then, the derivative functionÂ *fâ€™(t)*Â describes the runnerâ€™s speed at any timeÂ *t*.
    - If *s(t)*Â that describes the real-time sales of a particular product; the corresponding derivative functionÂ *sâ€™(t)*Â describes how those sales are changing in real-time.
- IfÂ ***fâ€™(x)*Â > 0**, the corresponding functionÂ *f(x)*Â is increasing. Keep in mind thatÂ *f(x)*Â itself may be negative even though the derivativeÂ *fâ€™(x)*Â is positive. The derivative says nothing about the value of the original function, only about how it is changing. Similarly, ifÂ *fâ€™(x)*Â < 0, then the original function is decreasing.
- IfÂ ***fâ€™(x)*Â = 0**, then the function is not changing. This can mean one of a few things.
    - It may mean that the function has reached aÂ ***local maximum*Â (or maxima)**. A local maximum is a value of x whereÂ *fâ€™(x)*Â changes from positive to negative and thus hits 0 along the way. InÂ *f(x)*, the local maximum is higher than all the points around it.
    - It may also mean that the function has reached what is called aÂ ***local minimum***. A local minimum is lower than the points around it. WhenÂ *fâ€™(x)*Â goes from negative values to 0 to positive values, a local minimum form.
    - It may be anÂ *inflection point*. This is a point where a function has a change in the direction of curvature. For example, the curve of the function goes from â€œfacing downâ€ to â€œfacing up.â€ Finding inflection points involves a second derivative test, which we will not get to in this lesson.
- *Global maxima*Â andÂ *global minima*Â are the largest or smallest over the entire range of a function.
- In machine learning models, maxima and minima are key concepts as theyâ€™re usually what we are trying to find when we optimize!

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/22f62ec6-eb17-4528-9c69-60e00714345b/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/293e910a-29bb-405f-b5f1-8bb5ab9b417f/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/50a2335f-5db1-467b-aeb0-652e538f0be2/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/f0f196e1-c735-4775-9f0f-eaa3cf5a448c/Untitled.png)

![Untitled](https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/secure.notion-static.com/2ec80af8-3598-4197-961e-fc46c6c10f4d/Untitled.png)

- What do we know about the value ofÂ *fâ€™(x)*Â in this section ofÂ *f(x) in the above 5 images, respectively?*
    1. *f'(x) > 0*Â because the slope of the function is positive.
    2. *f'(x) = 0*Â because the slope of the function is going from positive to negative and at the global maximum it is equal to zero.
    3. *f'(x) < 0*Â because the slope of the function is negative.
    4. *f'(x) = 0*Â because the slope of the function is going from negative to positive and at the local minimum it is equal to zero.
    5. *f'(x) = 0*Â because the slope of the function is going from positive to negative and at the local maximum it is equal to zero.

